<% content_for :title, "#{@post[:title]} | devopsellence blog" %>

<main class="page page-article">
  <header class="article-header">
    <p class="article-back"><%= link_to "&larr; Blog".html_safe, blog_path %></p>
    <p class="article-series-label"><%= @post[:series] %> &mdash; Part <%= @post[:part] %> of 7</p>
    <h1><%= @post[:title] %></h1>
    <div class="article-meta">
      <time><%= @post[:date].strftime("%B %-d, %Y") %></time>
      <span><%= @post[:reading_time] %></span>
    </div>
  </header>

  <article class="article-body">

    <p>Agents on your servers need to access GCP services: pull images from Artifact Registry, fetch desired state from Cloud Storage, resolve secrets from Secret Manager. The obvious approach is to create a GCP service account key and store it on each server. But that means a long-lived credential file sitting on every node in your fleet &mdash; a credential that can be exfiltrated, that doesn't expire, and that's hard to rotate.</p>

    <p>devopsellence uses <strong>Workload Identity Federation</strong> instead. No GCP credentials are stored on your servers. Agents obtain short-lived, scoped access tokens through a multi-step token exchange &mdash; and every token expires automatically.</p>

    <h2>The token exchange chain</h2>

    <p>Getting a GCP access token requires four steps. Each step narrows the scope and shortens the lifetime:</p>

    <div class="article-diagram">
      <div class="article-diagram-chain">
        <div class="article-diagram-chain-step">
          <div class="article-diagram-chain-num">1</div>
          <div class="article-diagram-chain-content">
            <strong>Subject token</strong>
            <p>The control plane issues a short-lived RS256 JWT to the agent (5-minute TTL). The JWT is scoped to a specific node, environment, and organization. It includes claims like <code>organization_id</code>, <code>environment_id</code>, <code>node_id</code>, <code>service_account_email</code>, and bundle tokens. The JWT is signed with the node identity key (Cloud KMS in production).</p>
          </div>
        </div>
        <div class="article-diagram-chain-step">
          <div class="article-diagram-chain-num">2</div>
          <div class="article-diagram-chain-content">
            <strong>STS exchange</strong>
            <p>The agent sends the JWT to Google Security Token Service (<code>sts.googleapis.com</code>) using the RFC 8693 token exchange grant type. Google verifies the JWT signature against the control plane's OIDC JWKS endpoint (<code>/.well-known/jwks.json</code>) and returns a federated access token.</p>
          </div>
        </div>
        <div class="article-diagram-chain-step">
          <div class="article-diagram-chain-num">3</div>
          <div class="article-diagram-chain-content">
            <strong>Service account impersonation</strong>
            <p>The agent uses the federated token to call <code>iamcredentials.googleapis.com</code> and impersonate the environment's dedicated GCP service account. This returns a short-lived access token (~1 hour) with the permissions of that service account.</p>
          </div>
        </div>
        <div class="article-diagram-chain-step">
          <div class="article-diagram-chain-num">4</div>
          <div class="article-diagram-chain-content">
            <strong>Scoped access</strong>
            <p>The access token can reach only the resources IAM allows: this environment's secrets in Secret Manager, this environment's desired state in GCS, and this organization's images in Artifact Registry.</p>
          </div>
        </div>
      </div>
    </div>

    <h2>Per-environment service accounts</h2>

    <p>Each environment gets its own GCP service account, created automatically during environment provisioning:</p>

    <div class="terminal">
      <div class="terminal-bar">
        <span class="dot dot-red"></span>
        <span class="dot dot-yellow"></span>
        <span class="dot dot-green"></span>
        <span class="terminal-bar-title">Per-environment identity</span>
      </div>
      <div class="terminal-body">
        <pre class="config-pre"><code># Each environment gets:
Service account:  eb{token}@{gcp-project}.iam.gserviceaccount.com

# With IAM bindings for:
roles/secretmanager.secretAccessor  → this env's secrets only
roles/storage.objectViewer          → this env's GCS path only
roles/iam.workloadIdentityUser      → this env's service account only</code></pre>
      </div>
    </div>

    <p>This is enforcement at the GCP IAM level. Even if an agent is misconfigured or compromised, the GCP access token it obtains can only reach the resources bound to its environment's service account. Cross-environment access is blocked by IAM, not by application logic.</p>

    <h2>Workload Identity Federation setup</h2>

    <p>The federation relies on OIDC (OpenID Connect). The control plane acts as an OIDC identity provider:</p>

    <ul>
      <li><strong>Discovery document</strong> at <code>/.well-known/openid-configuration</code> &mdash; tells Google where to find JWKS keys.</li>
      <li><strong>JWKS endpoint</strong> at <code>/.well-known/jwks.json</code> &mdash; publishes the public keys Google STS uses to verify subject tokens.</li>
      <li><strong>Workload Identity Pool</strong> &mdash; a GCP resource that trusts the control plane's OIDC issuer.</li>
      <li><strong>Workload Identity Provider</strong> &mdash; configured with attribute mappings (<code>google.subject</code>, <code>attribute.organization_id</code>, <code>attribute.project_id</code>) that constrain which JWTs are accepted.</li>
    </ul>

    <p>The attribute mappings are critical. They ensure that a JWT issued for Organization A, Environment B, Node C cannot be used to impersonate a service account belonging to a different organization or environment. The mapping is: JWT claims &rarr; WIF attributes &rarr; IAM principal set &rarr; service account binding.</p>

    <h2>Node authentication (separate from WIF)</h2>

    <p>Agents authenticate to the control plane itself (not to GCP) using a rotating token pair:</p>

    <ul>
      <li><strong>Bootstrap token</strong> &mdash; 32-byte random value, 1-hour TTL, single-use. Generated by <code>devopsellence node register</code> and consumed when the agent first calls in. After consumption, it can never be reused.</li>
      <li><strong>Access token</strong> &mdash; 1-hour TTL. Used for all control plane API calls (fetching subject tokens, reporting status, etc.).</li>
      <li><strong>Refresh token</strong> &mdash; 30-day TTL. Used to obtain new access/refresh token pairs. <strong>Both tokens rotate on every refresh</strong> &mdash; the previous pair is immediately invalidated.</li>
    </ul>

    <p>All tokens are stored as SHA256 digests in the database. The raw tokens are never persisted. This means a database compromise doesn't expose tokens that can be replayed &mdash; an attacker would need to reverse SHA256 to use a stolen digest.</p>

    <p>Revocation is immediate via a <code>revoked_at</code> timestamp on the node record. Setting this field invalidates all tokens for that node instantly.</p>

    <h2>What this gives you</h2>

    <ul>
      <li><strong>No stored GCP credentials.</strong> No service account key files on your servers. Nothing to exfiltrate.</li>
      <li><strong>Automatic rotation.</strong> Every token in the chain is short-lived and rotated automatically.</li>
      <li><strong>Immediate revocation.</strong> Revoking a node's identity in the control plane cuts off all GCP access.</li>
      <li><strong>Per-environment isolation.</strong> IAM bindings ensure agents can only access their own environment's resources.</li>
      <li><strong>Audit trail.</strong> Every token exchange and service account impersonation is logged in GCP.</li>
    </ul>

    <p>Next: <strong><%= link_to "Part 5 — TLS private keys that never leave your servers", blog_post_path(slug: "gcp-primitives-part-5-tls") %></strong></p>

  </article>

